  However, the announcements of recent days regarding new protests and the broadening of the strike suggest no swift end to the dispute, despite the return to the negotiating table on January 7. Nor did the end-of-year speech by President Emmanuel Macron arouse any hope, who affirmed that the reform, one of his campaign promises, would go ahead, in contact with the social actors who are willing to accompany it. On Friday, organizations led by the General Confederation of Labor (CGT), the most radical movement in the rejection of the reform bill, called a day of demonstrations on January 11, which adds to that already convened for January 9.